ing how capitalism shapes integral relations within the social whole.Contributors: Brent Ryan Bellamy, Sarah Brouillette, Sarika Chandra, Chris Chen,Joshua Clover, Tim Kreiner, Arthur Scarritt, Zoe Sutherland, Marina Vishmidt  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aIntersectionality (Sociology). 0aMarginality, Social. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh  aMarxist theory.  acontemporary social movements.  acritical race studies.  afeminism.  alabor history.  aracial capitalism.  asocial reproduction theory.1 aBellamy, Brent Ryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellamy, Brent Ryan.1 aBrouillette, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrouillette, Sarah.1 aChandra, Sarika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandra, Sarika, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChandra, Sarika.1 aChen, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Chris.1 aClover, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClover, Joshua.1 aFloyd, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFloyd, Kevin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKreiner, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreiner, Tim.1 aPhillis, Jen Hedler, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillis, Jen Hedler, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPhillis, Jen Hedler.1 aRyan Bellamy, Brent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScarritt, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScarritt, Arthur.1 aSutherland, 